ed": false, "mention": "nbsp", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.6723334789276123, "span": {"begin": 567, "end": 571}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "promoter regions", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8711419105529785, "span": {"begin": 583, "end": 599}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.7044457793235779, "span": {"begin": 603, "end": 615}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9973201751708984, "span": {"begin": 645, "end": 648}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9984025955200195, "span": {"begin": 649, "end": 653}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:581"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Bax", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9952297806739807, "span": {"begin": 708, "end": 711}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:581"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Bax protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9695947170257568, "span": {"begin": 762, "end": 773}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9953291416168213, "span": {"begin": 821, "end": 824}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9979591369628906, "span": {"begin": 958, "end": 961}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9977616667747498, "span": {"begin": 962, "end": 966}}], "text": "The mechanistic linkage between&nbsp;AhR/ARNT dimerization and Bax upregulation&nbsp;is supported by molecular biology and toxicology studies. The&nbsp;aryl hydrocarbon receptor (AhR)&nbsp;is a ligand-activated transcription factor that, upon binding to xenobiotics such as&nbsp;polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, translocates into the nucleus and forms a heterodimeric complex with&nbsp;AhR nuclear translocator (ARNT). This dimerization is an essential step for AhR&rsquo;s transcriptional activity, as it enables binding to&nbsp;xenobiotic response elements (XREs)&nbsp;within the promoter regions of target genes.&nbsp;Activation of the&nbsp;AhR/ARNT complex&nbsp;has been shown to directly regulate&nbsp;Bax transcription, leading to increased expression of Bax protein. This aligns with the well-established role of AhR in modulating gene expression through&nbsp;XRE-dependent transcriptional activation. The structural and functional interplay between AhR/ARNT and the transcriptional machinery further supports the plausibility of this Key Event Relationship.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:15:14 +0000 2026"}